        "gg4x74DfD4w_text": "<p>Ever stare at those piles of tees you <i>knew</i> were gonna sell, but now you only watch them gather dust in the corner? Yeah—That’s the classic stock-printing headache.You spend a chunk in the beginning, hoping the designs could pop. But when they don’t, you’re left with wasted money and shelves full of “maybe next season.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Here’s the twist in the story: the Direct To Garment print method completely changes the paradigm. There is no need to guess or stock up on inventory.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Do you need a T-shirt? Print it—and done. Want to create hype for a drop with only 20 shirts? Easy. Got a last minute event that is coming up? No Problem. Do you want to start a mini merch business that is located in your garage? You can do that too.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>If you are looking to impress, the Procolored <a href=\"https://www.procolored.com/collections/dtg-printer\" target=\"_blank\"><u>Direct To Garment printers</u></a> are insane. The colors are extremely vibrant, and the details are meticulous and you do not need to print in bulk in order to achieve a professional look.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>You can print one or one hundred. Each one has the same high quality, as if the order was for bulk printing. Turns high risk, single prints and last minute orders into business profits.</p>",
        "gg6hbemm9Bc_text": "<p>Nothing beats the adrenaline rush of getting your hands on a shiny new DTG printer. But, heads up, the DTG printer doesn’t run the show—your plan does. So, how do you turn this gear into an actual profit machine and not just an expensive room decoration? Let’s talk, step-by-step:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>0-30 days: Get Set Up and Sample-ready</strong></p><p>Set up the DTG printer, get training, and get your color profiles lock on. Start printing out your best designs samples on every type of fabric and colors you can find. Show off what this printer can do. And if you’re selling online, don’t skip the mockup plugin—people wanna see what their stuff looks like before they spend cash.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Day 31 to 90: Test and Launch</strong></p><p>Roll out your first “starter bundles” or plan up some merch kits for local events. Market those sample kits to nearby businesses—get people touching your work. Don’t get lazy on the backend, either; smooth out everything from order intake to shipping labels. Somewhere in this stretch you should bag your first legit business client, no lie.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>91-180 days:Scale and Diversify</strong></p><p>By this point, you should know what’s getting love, and what’s gathering dust. Double down on what’s hot—add event printing, chase down brand collabs, maybe kick off a subscription box (surprise shirt of the month, anyone?). Try out new products, fabrics, whatever gets you hyped. If orders are spiking up, it’s time to hire, automate, or pick another machine or even outsource for overflow jobs</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Basically, you’re not just running a printer anymore. You’re building an engine—a business that gets stronger every month.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Side note: Procolored <a href=\"https://www.procolored.com/collections/dtg-printer\" target=\"_blank\"><u>DTG printers</u></a> make all this way less stressful, because they’re reliable and you don’t need a PhD to run them. Every step feels doable, not like you’re drowning in a tech sea. So yeah, the real magic’s just getting started.</p>",
