        "ggXVyTcVVK3_text": "Subscribe",
        "ggXgmpXipgu_text": "<p>Having a <a href=\"https://www.procolored.com/collections/dtg-printer\" target=\"_blank\"><u>DTG printer</u></a> isn’t enough to win over customers—how you market it to them is what edges the competition in today’s flooded merch market. The mantra is: <i><strong>‘Show, Don’t Tell’.</strong></i></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>● Tell Stories, Not Statistics:</strong> People love feeling a part of the magic. Show behind-the-scenes snippets of how a design transforms from a digital sketch to a printed and cured piece in under an hour. This approach exposes the speed and flexibility of your setup while allowing your audience to feel the magic.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>● Turn Samples Into Sales Tools</strong>: Don’t just say you provide value, instead, prove it. Send sample kits containing both light and dark prints, or various different fabrics, to let clients touch and see the Procolored’s color accuracy and softness. There’s nothing that closes a deal faster than a shirt.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>● Productize Your Services:</strong> Don’t just sell printing. Offer your “Design + Print Starter Pack” to new brands, “Pop-up Merch Kits” for events, or a “Corporate Event Rush” that delivers branded shirts in record time. Customers adore how easy the packages make decisions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>● Market To Everyone:</strong> Go where your buyers hang out. Pitch boutiques, team up at pop-ups, show out at trade events, whatever works. And please, leverage TikTok and Insta Reels—nothing turns heads like a printing time-lapse racking up views.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>● Flexible Pricing Models</strong>. Offer options that match different sets of customers. Per-item for newbies, monthly deals for those ordering in bulk, maybe lease-to-own financing if somebody wants their own Procolored DTG printer. The more ways in, the bigger your audience.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The printer is just your ticket in—Procolored’s got the color and print game on lock. Stack that up with sick stories, real-life samples, and packages people actually understand, and you’re doing way more than selling tees. You’re building a crew of loyal customers who stick around for the whole ride.</p>",
        "ggXp_zyGABK_text": "<p>Once you’ve got your first few orders, the next step is figuring out how to grow without adding risk? Well, a DTG printer can be a total game-changer if you play it right. Here’s how you’d go about it.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>● First up, don’t just stick to one marketplace. Cross-list your <a href=\"https://www.procolored.com/collections/dtg-printer\" target=\"_blank\"><u>DTG print</u></a> everywhere—Amazon, Etsy, even that local artisan market while also shipping under other brands’ labels (white-label). . You’ll look way bigger than you actually are. Fake it until you make it, right?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>● And for real, stop trying to do all the art yourself. Get some local talent involved and pay them a share on every sale. They hand you cool designs, you don’t shell out any cash upfront, everyone’s happy. Plus, it keeps your catalog looking fresh, like it’s always on trend.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>● Subscriptions are your real deal. Set up steady monthly deals with school, club, or quirky local shops on a regular delivery. Now you’re not sitting there praying for another random order to drop in—you’ve got steady income rolling in, month after month.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>● And this is big: automate what you can. Use tools like Barcode tracking, job queue and batch curing instead of doing one by one. If you try doing all this by hand as you scale, you’ll probably end up hiding under your own print table, trust me.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The beauty is, with a <a href=\"https://www.procolored.com/\" target=\"_blank\"><u>Procolored</u></a> DTG printer actually in your corner, scaling up doesn't mean stress—it means turning your side hustle kinda looks like a real-deal brand.</p>",
